value.0: Kenku are small, halfling sized humanoids with the body features (feet, head, body covred in feathers) of a crow or a raven. They have working, prehensile talon ended hands, but no wings, and are exceptionally good at working together. Many Kenku become thieves, using their teamwork skills to pull off impressive heists.
This kobold carries herself with a sense of intelligence and utmost propriety.

A silky robe it may appear to the normal eye, but as you look closely to the robe's fine cloth, it seems hardened and imbued with small bits of metal.  This may proove useful for defense, and you can certainly feel this has magical properties as well.
This tall man seems rugged from many sea journeys. Many pouches and tools betray he's an artificer of sorts. He seems very occupied with various trinkets and reagents, clearly crafting things.

Value.value: Ah, yes. What wonders can I cra- *squints, looking you up and down* You another one of those fresh bloods looking for a recall stone?
Tell you what. I got a bunch of them ready to ship to Cetha. If you run a few errands for me, I might just drop one and not notice. *winks and laughs*
Run to the market for me and hand my boy Gull this paper. *hands over a grocery list*
Aaah there you are. All done? My fees and ship are in order? Splendid! Now let me get back to my work. *turns around to lift a crate, dropping a blank recall stone on the floor without looking back*
Did you give my grocery list to Gull in the market yet? Remember to also check my docking status with Gliffy in the harbor.
I'm pretty busy right now. You already have a Recall Stone, so leave me be.
Then head to the dock to verify my docking fee and documents are in order. I believe Gliffy is responsible for that. She's a lovely bald woman. *laughs* Come back when you're done.

This portly man stands beside various boxes of trading goods with a notebook in hand, seemingly always taking inventory.  Most notably this man has an eye patch, which for some reason matches that of the dog beside him.

Clad in fine leather and chain armor this gruff sounding yet sophisticated looking man is clearly one of authority within the Moorhound Company. With a gait of an experienced swordsman, he seems as one who is most familiar and comfortable on the high seas.

This armor seems to be the ceremonial regalia of a Maskarran priest.  Done in a motley pattern, this clothing emphasizes freedom of movement and speed over all things.  It also has an unusual side effect: while wearing this clothing, thoughts of larceny and ways to attempt it come unbidden to your mind.
This wand will allow a seasoned tracker to identify any one creature within a zone.

This finely-dressed magus has a deeply magical aura. And beneath that, something that makes the hair on the back of your neck stand up.

The guildmaster of the Ebon Wyrm appears focused on other matters.

One of the many designed staves by the Axis nation, these benefit the arcane caster the ability to focus more into a specific school.  Powerful and helpful; these staves prove useful for both wizard and sorcerer that seek to master their school.

value.0: An adventurer and member of the Ebon Wyrm.

If ever there were a bow to signify a person's standing in a wood, it'd be this bow. The bow itself has been lovingly carved from only the finest material. A permanent Ironwood spell and a fine bowstring ensure any arrow notched in this bow will fly quite true.

Additionally, many druid spells have been cast on this bow allowing it to boost the wielder's ability to see her enemy. Only ones familiar and understanding about nature may pluck the bowstring, others will snap it.

This cloak is an intricate weaving of hearty forest leaves, created in the forest grove by a circle of rangers and druids.  It emanates the very life force of the forest itself, healing the bearer's wounds as they appear.  In the hands of a ranger, this accessory becomes a valuable tool, aiding in most of her abilities in some way or another.

value.0: An adventurer and member of the Ebon Wyrm.

The blackguards are the only ones who know where this dark armor is actually made, and they are not telling.  One could assume because of the outstanding quality and dark magics intertwined that perhaps some demon, or dark ally has forged this for them.  Regardless, any class may wear this suit, provided that their heart is as black as pitch.

In the accursed shadows of the infested property of Earl Manfried in Kohlingen, Sir Grogan the Valiant brandished the Ghostfire maul, a colossal weapon forged to bring retribution upon the undead that plagued the manor. Carved with holy inscriptions and emanating a divine radiance, the great maul became a beacon of purity against the encroaching darkness. As Sir Grogan swung the Ghostfire, its enchanted head collided with skeletal adversaries, sending shockwaves of positive energy that shattered bones and banished the undead to eternal rest. With each resounding strike, the maul's luminescence intensified, illuminating the haunted halls and transforming Sir Grogan into a relentless force of vengeance against the terrors that disturbed the sanctity of the Holy City.

Decades later, the legendary Ghostfire maul can be found outside of the lands of Kohlingen. It is said that Sir Grogan's squires went on to commission these weapons in his honor - and they were lost alongside them in their many campaigns against undead.

This helmet has been exquisitely forged from adamantine, its sinisterly beautiful design typical of drow craftsmanship. A small letter "V" has been interwoven into the pattern upon the visor.

Adamantine is an extraordinarily hard alloy that is almost impenetrable to normal weapons. Deposits of adamant are usually found near areas of Faerzress in the Underdark, and to the Deep Denizens it is usually black in colour, though it possesses a green sheen when viewed by natural light or a purple-white sheen when viewed by magical light.

This kit contains the various tools and liquids needed for a skilled assassin to perform and execute her special underhanded techniques. Every last bit of this equipment seem engineered towards a single minded purpose; killing its target as efficiently as possible. As the assassin's skill progresses, so does the complexity of her attacks and techniques.

//OOC Note: To use these techniques, simply use the kit and select which one to use. All of these abilities have a cooldown of 60 seconds once a target has been hit by this (saving throw rolled, not successful roll). The cooldown is universal and will persist for 60 seconds even if you change which ability to use//

Braining Blow (Stun) (2 rounds, will)
Head injuries are especially traumatic, and the Assassin knows this. Heavy, blunt force dealt by a pommel or leaden arrow can temporarily stun a foe, leaving them vulnerable to a follow-up strike.

Shrill Strike (Deafness) (Turn/assassin, fort)
The importance of the sense of hearing in combat is not lost on the Assassin. An attack upon the auditory organs leaves the ears of the Assassin's foe ringing painfully.

Beshaba's Favor (-d4 all stats) (supernatural permanent, doesn't stack, will)
The Assassin becomes adept at turning disadvantage to advantage, weakness into strength, bad luck into blessed fortune. Provided, that this misfortune falls upon the Assassin's victim.

Stalker's Throat-Dart (Silence) (1 round/ assassin, fort)
Landing a blow to the throat is one of the most difficult attacks an Assassin can make. By no chance, it is also one of the most rewarding.

Induce Amaurosis (Blindness) (1 round/assassin, fort)
The Assassin knows that something as innocuous as a culinary spice can have more malign uses. Pepper, thrown into the eyes of the foe in the heat of battle, leaves them a bit burned.

Blade of Terror (Paralysis) (1 round/assassin, will save to counter)
The appalling viciousness of the Assassin's assault cows the target into submission. The assassin may make a death-attack that causes overwhelming fear to the target of this ability.

Bloodlet (Leveldrain) (supernatrual permanent stacks, fort)
The Carotid and Femoral artery are prime targets for a cutting or piercing strike. An accurate slice can cause the most extreme case of profuse bleeding: untreated, such a strike is as good as a death-sentence.

Kneecapper's Knife (Knockdown) (Rounds/3Assassin, reflex)
The legs are a promising, if difficult to hit, target. They are often more lightly armored than the torso, as even the most rigid plate armor has many joints and thin parts in its metal.

Murder (Death, death ward ignored, fort)
The most valuable and feared tool at the Assassin's disposal is not their famed agility or skill with blade or bow, but their knowledge of anatomy and flagrant disregard for the niceties of honorable combat. This attack leaves nothing about the Assassin's motives to question. A feint, a flash of steel from the shadows, or a careful shot: a strike made with the intent to bring their target down instantly, no matter the cost.
